04020nam a22005295i 9780773563230DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19931993xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735632307 a10.1515/97807735632302doi  a(DE-B1597)655139  a(OCoLC)1394872952  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHN425.5 ǂb H27 1993eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306/.09441 aForsé, Michel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRecent Social Trends in France, 1960-1990 /cJean-Pierre Jaslin, Michel Forsé. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1993] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Charting of Social Change ;v400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tContext -- tAge Groups -- tMicrosocial -- tWomen -- tLabour Market -- tLabour and Management -- tSocial Stratification -- tSocial Relations -- tState and Service Institutions -- tMobilizing Institutions -- tInstitutionalization of Social Forces -- tIdeologies -- tHousehold Resources -- tLife Style -- tLeisure -- tEducational Attainment -- tIntegration and Marginalization -- tAttitudes and Values0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA prominent feature of the social revolution in France has been the decline of the great national institutions -- the Republic, the Army, the church, and the schools -- which are losing their symbolic value and are no longer the targets of ideological disputes. As a result, there is a growing basic consensus among the French people. At the same time, the French have developed a new interest in managing local problems -- due to the decentralization law -- which has led to the establishment of many voluntary associations. Changes in family life following the "revolution" of 1968 have led to greater instability among couples, but at the same time have strengthened the kinship system resulting in increased life expectancy. The customs of the French have also changed. The French education system, originally based on authority and regulations, is now making increasing use of experimentation and negotiation. As a result, the attitude of the French towards authority has totally changed and the French have learned to negotiate and cooperate among themselves. All these changes can be interpreted as progressive moves toward liberty, equality, and individualism. There is little danger of social instability, since French society remains in remarkably robust health.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aJaslin, Jean-Pierre, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356323040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773563230423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773563230/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles